*INDUSIND BANK LTD. (IB) Updated Jan.19*

Background:

IndusInd Bank was set up in 1994 and is part of the Hinduja Group. The
Hinduja group is based in London, UK and its best known brands are
Ashok Leyland and Gulf Oil. IB was set up in Mumbai but is now based
in Pune. It was promoted by IndusInd Enterprises and Finance Ltd along
with five Mauritius based companies. Mr.Ramesh Sobti is the current MD
& CEO since 2007-08. He had worked with SBI, ANZ Grindlays and ABN
Amro,
in that order, previously.

Shareholding:

The shares were listed in 1997. Its current promoter holding is 12.3%
by IndusInd International Holdings Ltd. and 4.44% by IndusInd Ltd. for
a total of 16.74% (as of Sept.18). Both are Mauritius based companies.
The entire holding of IndusInd Ltd. is pledged. It may be noted that
this data is from the declaration to BSE and available on the
exchange’s site. By contrast, the AR for FY18 shows 14.97% (11 +
3.97) by
including the shares underlying Depository Receipts in the total
shares outstanding.

For the rest, MFs hold 9.44% and FPIs hold 52.2%. Only one shareholder
holds more than 3% - Bridge India Fund, a FPI, holds 3.92% as of
September 18.

Subsidiaries:

ALF Insurance Services Pvt. Ltd., a 100% subsidiary, was voluntarily
liquidated in 2016. IndusInd Marketing and Financial Services Pvt.
Ltd., an associate company in which IB holds 30%, is in the field of
providing manpower services. It is a profit making concern.

IB has recently (June 18) completed acquiring 100% stake in IL&FS
Securities Services Ltd, the securities services subsidiary of IL&FS.
This and the purchase of securities financing portfolio from IL&FS
Financial Services Ltd. was started in FY17. The regulatory approvals
are in place but closure has not yet taken place due to ‘pending
fulfillment of certain conditions by the
counterparties’.

IB is in the process of merging Bharat Financial Inclusion Ltd (BFIL),
a quoted microfinance company, with itself on a stock swap basis. BFIL
was formerly known as SKS Microfinance Ltd. BFIL is a profit making
company. The merger seeks to let IB make a mark in the microfinance
field and venture out from cities to the hinterland. BFIL is stated to
have been working with IB as a Business Correspondent for some time
and,
thus, both companies are share a work-culture.

General:

IB acquired Royal Bank of Scotland's Diamond & Jewellery Financing
business in India in 2015 as a step towards focussing on gems and
jewellery group, particularly the diamond cutting and polishing for
exports industry. As a result, the gems and jewellery sector forms the
largest component of the corporate loan book as of Mar.18 at 5.18% of
total advances but it is now (Dec.18) below the 5% mark. The
additional
provisioning as a result of recent scams in the sector have been small
in IB’s case. The MD claims that this is due to the fact that their
lending is more to the diamond processing industry and not the
jewellery sector which was the worse affected of the two.

Financials:

GNPA level is stated to be 1.13% as of December 2018. The Net NPA is a
meagre 0.59%. Noticeably, they have no exposure to any industry beyond
5% of their loan book, thus diversifying their lending risk.

Perhaps because of the large financing of export-imports, they have a
large contingent liability for forward exchange and derivative
contracts but the financials present a sound picture with no cause for
alarm. Their borrowings from outside India have also grown more than
3-fold during FY18. As against this, they appear to have several risk
management systems in place.

They have made a contingent provision of Rs.275 cr. towards their
exposure to IL&FS in QE September 2018, despite treating the
facilities as Standard Assets in accordance with RBI guidelines. The
full extent of such exposure is not mentioned.

Bonds:

The 9.5% unsecured perpetual bonds issued in April 2017 are currently
being offered at 10.10% Yield. They have a Call option in April 2022.
The bonds’ rating of AA Stable outlook was reaffirmed by both CRISIL
and India Ratings & Research in March 2018. A measure of the bank’s
stability is that the ratings agencies have not felt the need to
re-look their ratings since March. The ratings are good because it
permits the large institutions such as insurance companies to invest
in these bonds, lending liquidity.

Conclusion:

The strength of the balance sheet combine well with the higher return
offered by these bonds (comparing with other Perpetual debt
instruments PDI) make it a good investment. The only higher yield PDIs
are from riskier sick PSBs. The return also compares well with non PDI
debt instruments available. A decent buy on a medium term outlook.

