<p style="margin:0cm; margin-bottom:.0001pt; margin-right:0cm; margin-left:0cm">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><b><u><span style="font-size:14.0pt">INDUSIND BANK LTD. (IB) Updated Jan.19</span></u></b></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><u><span style="font-size:14.0pt">Background:</span></u></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">IndusInd Bank was set up in 1994 and is part of the Hinduja Group. The Hinduja group is based in London, UK and its best known brands are Ashok Leyland and Gulf Oil. IB was set up in Mumbai but is now based in Pune. It was promoted by IndusInd Enterprises and Finance Ltd along with five Mauritius based companies. Mr.Ramesh Sobti is the current MD &amp; CEO since 2007-08. He had worked with SBI, ANZ Grindlays and ABN Amro,
in that order, previously.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><u><span style="font-size:14.0pt">Shareholding:</span></u></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">The shares were listed in 1997. Its current promoter holding is 12.3% by IndusInd International Holdings Ltd. and 4.44% by IndusInd Ltd. for a total of 16.74% (as of Sept.18). Both are Mauritius based companies. The entire holding of IndusInd Ltd. is pledged. It may be noted that this data is from the declaration to BSE and available on the exchange&rsquo;s site. By contrast, the AR for FY18 shows 14.97% (11 + 3.97) by
including the shares underlying Depository Receipts in the total shares outstanding.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">For the rest, MFs hold 9.44% and FPIs hold 52.2%. Only one shareholder holds more than 3% - Bridge India Fund, a FPI, holds 3.92% as of September 18.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><u><span style="font-size:14.0pt">Subsidiaries:</span></u></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">ALF Insurance Services Pvt. Ltd., a 100% subsidiary, was voluntarily liquidated in 2016. IndusInd Marketing and Financial Services Pvt. Ltd., an associate company in which IB holds 30%, is in the field of providing manpower services. It is a profit making concern.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">IB has recently (June 18) completed acquiring 100% stake in IL&amp;FS Securities Services Ltd, the securities services subsidiary of IL&amp;FS. This and the purchase of securities financing portfolio from IL&amp;FS Financial Services Ltd. was started in FY17. The regulatory approvals are in place but closure has not yet taken place due to &lsquo;pending fulfillment of certain conditions by the
counterparties&rsquo;.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">IB is in the process of merging Bharat Financial Inclusion Ltd (BFIL), a quoted microfinance company, with itself on a stock swap basis. BFIL was formerly known as SKS Microfinance Ltd. BFIL is a profit making company. The merger seeks to let IB make a mark in the microfinance field and venture out from cities to the hinterland. BFIL is stated to have been working with IB as a Business Correspondent for some time and,
thus, both companies are share a work-culture.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><u><span style="font-size:14.0pt">General:</span></u></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">IB acquired Royal Bank of Scotland&#39;s Diamond &amp; Jewellery Financing business in India in 2015 as a step towards focussing on gems and jewellery group, particularly the diamond cutting and polishing for exports industry. As a result, the gems and jewellery sector forms the largest component of the corporate loan book as of Mar.18 at 5.18% of total advances but it is now (Dec.18) below the 5% mark. The additional
provisioning as a result of recent scams in the sector have been small in IB&rsquo;s case. The MD claims that this is due to the fact that their lending is more to the diamond processing industry and not the jewellery sector which was the worse affected of the two.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><u><span style="font-size:14.0pt">Financials:</span></u></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">GNPA level is stated to be 1.13% as of December 2018. The Net NPA is a meagre 0.59%. Noticeably, they have no exposure to any industry beyond 5% of their loan book, thus diversifying their lending risk.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">Perhaps because of the large financing of export-imports, they have a large contingent liability for forward exchange and derivative contracts but the financials present a sound picture with no cause for alarm. Their borrowings from outside India have also grown more than 3-fold during FY18. As against this, they appear to have several risk management systems in place.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">They have made a contingent provision of Rs.275 cr. towards their exposure to IL&amp;FS in QE September 2018, despite treating the facilities as Standard Assets in accordance with RBI guidelines. The full extent of such exposure is not mentioned.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><u><span style="font-size:14.0pt">Bonds:</span></u></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">The 9.5% unsecured perpetual bonds issued in April 2017 are currently being offered at 10.10% Yield. They have a Call option in April 2022. The bonds&rsquo; rating of AA Stable outlook was reaffirmed by both CRISIL and India Ratings &amp; Research in March 2018. A measure of the bank&rsquo;s stability is that the ratings agencies have not felt the need to re-look their ratings since March. The ratings are good because it
permits the large institutions such as insurance companies to invest in these bonds, lending liquidity.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm
0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><u><span style="font-size:14.0pt">Conclusion:</span></u></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="text-autospace:none"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:14.0pt">The strength of the balance sheet combine well with the higher return offered by these bonds (comparing with other Perpetual debt instruments PDI) make it a good investment. The only higher yield PDIs are from riskier sick PSBs. The return also compares well with non PDI debt instruments available. A decent buy on a medium term outlook.</span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="margin:0cm 0cm 0.0001pt">&nbsp;</p>
